e was from the sessions history.\\n\\nLooking at the data, I can see from the previous cron session (e7885813, 18:25 UTC) what the baseline was:\\n\\n**Baseline from last report (18:25 UTC):**\\n- cron:ed2d0b5d ✅ running\\n- cron:6f3323ef ✅ running\\n- cron:e7885813 ✅ running\\n- telegram:group:-5163901258 ✅ running\\n- telegram:direct:6053576134 ✅ done (normal cycle end)\\n\\n\\n- telegram:group:-5163901258 ✅ running (updatedAt 18:23 UTC)\\n\\nNow I'm checking the current state at 18:41 UTC. The cron sessions are all still running with updatedAt timestamps from around 18:25-18:35 UTC, so they've been cycling normally. I need to verify the telegram:group session as well. So the cron:e7885813 session that ran at 18:25 UTC was actually a subagent spawned by the earlier cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e instance, not a fresh cron execution. The original cron itself is still active and running normally, so this subagent session is just a child of that ongoing process. So the subagent from that cron session successfully delivered the message to Lead via Telegram, and then the subagent session itself ended.\\n\\nLooking at the current state at 18:41 UTC, I can see the cron:e7885813 session is still running with the same parent session key, and there are three other cron sessions all marked as running normally. The telegram group and direct sessions are also active, and I'm checking the main session to see if it started after the earlier heartbeat cycle ended.\\n\\nNow I'm cross-referencing the baseline from 18:25 UTC—the cron:e7885813 session was running then, and the cron:ed2d0b5d session had just started, along with a separate subagent session that sent the report to Lead.\\n\\nLooking at the current 18:41 UTC state, I can see the cron:e7885813 session is still running after 16 minutes, the cron:ed2d0b5d session is actively running, and there's a new main heartbeat session that started at 18:24 UTC, which wasn't in the baseline. The telegram:group session also appears to be running.\\n\\nComparing against the last stable state from the prior cycle, the main heartbeat session is the new addition—everything else (the three cron sessions and the telegram:group) appears unchanged. I need to double-check whether the main session was already counted as active in the previous report or if this is genuinely new. Let me recount the sessions properly—I need to filter out the cron session I'm currently in, then categorize what's left. Looking at the 39 total sessions, I'm focusing on the master-orchestrator sessions that are actually running, excluding subagents and done states. From what I can see, cron:e7885813, cron:ed2d0b5d, cron:6f3323ef, the main heartbeat session, and the telegram group are all running, though I should verify if the cron:e7885813 instance is still active or if it ended. I'm calculating the elapsed time for each cron session—e7885813 is running at 50 minutes 35 seconds, ed2d0b5d at 50 minutes 50 seconds, and 6f3323ef is the longest at 1 hour 1 minute 12 seconds since it started at 18:23:56. The telegram:group session is also running with an endedAt timestamp that I need to compare against the updatedAt time to determine if it's still active.\\n\\nLooking at the messages, the telegram:group session actually ended at 17:42:03 UTC and stayed dead until a new instance reactivated it at 18:25 UTC, so it's been running for about 16 minutes. The telegram:direct session ended normally at 18:02 UTC, which was expected from the baseline.\\n\\nSo comparing against the last known state, all three cron sessions are still running with no changes since the last report, and the telegram:group is stable as well. The pipeline appears to be in good shape.\\n\\nNow I'm trying to pinpoint exactly when the new main heartbeat session started—it looks like it was around 18:24 UTC based on the updatedAt timestamp, but I need to verify this against the session's start time to get the precise duration. The heartbeat cycles are running every 20 minutes with a new one spawning, so the system is stable and healthy. There are no state transitions to report, which means I should exit silently per the instructions. Let me quickly verify this is consistent with the previous run's analysis before concluding.\\n\\nLooking back at the last stable state from 17:51 UTC, all three critical sessions were running and the telegram group had ended normally around 17:42. Everything has remained consistent since then—cron:e7885813 restarted around 18:25, and the telegram group came back online at the same time. No new failures, blockers, or state transitions have occurred, so this is still a silent exit.\\n\\nActually, I should reconsider the main heartbeat session. It ended at 18:24 UTC and a new one started at 18:24 UTC, which means it's been running for about 17 minutes. But looking at the session details, the main session only runs for about 5 seconds per heartbeat and completes immediately, so it being \\\"running\\\" in the sessions list might just mean it spawned a new child that's handling the heartbeat. Either way, there's no actual change to report from the pipeline perspective.\\n\\nEverything is stable—cron jobs are running on schedule, Telegram sessions are active, and the pipeline is healthy. I'm done.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"**Silent exit — no state transitions.**\\n\\n**Current state (18:41 UTC) vs baseline (18:25 UTC):**\\n\\n| Session | Baseline | Current | Δ |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| cron:e7885813 | ✅ running | ✅ running | — |\\n| cron:ed2d0b5d | ✅ running | ✅ running | — |\\n| cron:6f3323ef | ✅ running | ✅ running | — |\\n| telegram:group:-5163901258 | ✅ running | ✅ running | — |\\n| telegram:direct:6053576134 | done | done | — |\\n\\nAll pipeline components stable. No new failures. No blockers. No report sent.\"\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n          \"provider\": \"ahvholding\",\n 